HEADWORD: Scath
<hw>Scath</hw> <pr>(sk⟦acr⟧th; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel.
<ets>ska⟦edh⟧i</ets>; akin to Dan. <ets>skade</ets>, Sw.
<ets>skada</ets>, AS. <ets>scea⟦edh⟧a</ets>, <ets>sca⟦edh⟧a</ets>, foe,
injurer, OS. <ets>ska⟦edh⟧o</ets>, D. <ets>schade</ets>, harm, injury,
OHG. <ets>scade</ets>, G. <ets>schade</ets>, <ets>schaden</ets>; cf. Gr.
<grk>'askhqh`s</grk> unharmed. Cf. <er>Scathe</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety>
<def>Harm; damage; injury; hurt; waste; misfortune.</def>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>scathe</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But she was somedeal deaf, and that was <qex>skathe</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Great mercy, sure, for to enlarge a thrall,⟦br⟧
Whose freedom shall thee turn to greatest <qex>scath</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wherein Rome hath done you any <qex>scath</qex>,⟦br⟧
Let him make treble satisfaction.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

